1 Introduction
**************

Gnosis is a personal knowledge management and spaced repetition system
for Emacs.  It integrates two complementary subsystems in a single
package: a Zettelkasten-style note system called *nodes*, and a
flashcard-based self-testing system built around *themata*.  Both
subsystems share a single SQLite database, and their contents are
designed to be linked together so that flashcard questions can refer
directly to the notes they are drawn from.

   The name gnosis (Greek: _γνῶσις_, knowledge) reflects the package's
philosophical orientation: the goal is not mere memorization but the
deliberate construction of knowledge over time.

* Menu:

* Why Gnosis::
* The Two Subsystems::
* Greek Terminology Reference::
* Data Storage::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Why Gnosis,  Next: The Two Subsystems,  Up: Introduction

1.1 Why Gnosis
==============

Most spaced repetition tools treat flashcards as isolated units.  You
create a card, review it, and the system schedules the next review.  The
cards have no relationship to each other or to anything outside the
review loop.

   Most note-taking tools do the opposite: they help you build a web of
interconnected ideas, but they offer no mechanism for systematically
testing and reinforcing what you have written.

   Gnosis bridges these two approaches.  Your notes and your review
material live in the same system, linked together.  When you write a
node about a topic, you can create themata whose questions reference
that node.  When you review, you can review all the questions linked to
a given note, or follow the link graph to review related topics.  The
goal is a single system where understanding and recall reinforce each
other.


