* GPG Encryption: GPG Encryption (1).
* Templates: Templates (1).
* ``TODO'' Integration::
* Checked Item Tracking::
* Inserting Journal Links::
* Full Journal Configuration Example::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Creating Entries,  Next: File vs Single-File Mode,  Up: Journal

4.1 Creating Entries
====================

* Menu:

* gnosis-journal::
* gnosis-journal-find::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: gnosis-journal,  Next: gnosis-journal-find,  Up: Creating Entries

4.1.1 ‘gnosis-journal’
----------------------

The quickest way to open today's journal entry is ‘gnosis-journal’.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: gnosis-journal-find,  Prev: gnosis-journal,  Up: Creating Entries

4.1.2 ‘gnosis-journal-find’
---------------------------

‘gnosis-journal-find’ accepts an optional title argument.  Called
interactively without arguments, it prompts for an existing or new
journal entry title via completing-read.  If the entry already exists,
gnosis opens it; if it does not, gnosis creates a new file (or heading,
in single-file mode) for it.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: File vs Single-File Mode,  Next: GPG Encryption (1),  Prev: Creating Entries,  Up: Journal

4.2 File vs Single-File Mode
============================

Gnosis supports two modes for journal storage:

* Menu:

* Separate Files (Default)::
* Single Journal File::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Separate Files (Default),  Next: Single Journal File,  Up: File vs Single-File Mode

4.2.1 Separate Files (Default)
------------------------------

By default, each journal entry is its own file in ‘gnosis-journal-dir’.
File naming follows the same rules as nodes (timestamp prefix by
default, configurable via ‘gnosis-nodes-timestring’).

     ;; Default: separate files per entry
     (setopt gnosis-journal-file nil)


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Single Journal File,  Prev: Separate Files (Default),  Up: File vs Single-File Mode

4.2.2 Single Journal File
-------------------------

Setting ‘gnosis-journal-file’ to a file path causes all journal entries
to be added as top-level headings in that file.  Each entry is a ‘*
YYYY-MM-DD’ heading with an org ID.

     (setopt gnosis-journal-file "~/Notes/journal/journal.org")

   When this is set, gnosis creates the file if it does not exist,
adding an appropriate ‘#+title:’ and ‘#+filetags:’ header.  New entries
are appended at the end of the file.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: GPG Encryption (1),  Next: Templates (1),  Prev: File vs Single-File Mode,  Up: Journal

4.3 GPG Encryption
==================

Like nodes, journal files can be created with a ‘.gpg’ suffix.  The
option ‘gnosis-journal-as-gpg’ controls this independently from
‘gnosis-nodes-create-as-gpg’.

     (setopt gnosis-journal-as-gpg nil)  ; default


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Templates (1),  Next: ``TODO'' Integration,  Prev: GPG Encryption (1),  Up: Journal

4.4 Templates
=============

Journal templates follow the same mechanism as node templates.  They are
configured via ‘gnosis-journal-templates’.

* Menu:

* gnosis-journal-templates::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: gnosis-journal-templates,  Up: Templates (1)

4.4.1 ‘gnosis-journal-templates’
--------------------------------

     (setopt gnosis-journal-templates
             '(("Default" (lambda ()
                            (concat "{*} Daily Notes\n\n"
                                    "{*} Goals\n"
                                    (gnosis-journal-todos))))
               ("Empty" (lambda () ""))))

   The default template calls ‘gnosis-journal-todos’, which produces a
checkbox list of any TODO items from ‘gnosis-journal-todo-files’ that
are due today (or have no scheduled date).  The ‘{*}’ heading marker
works exactly as in node templates.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: ``TODO'' Integration,  Next: Checked Item Tracking,  Prev: Templates (1),  Up: Journal

4.5 "TODO" Integration
======================

The journal module can pull TODO items from your org agenda files into
each journal entry as checkboxes.  This provides a daily task list drawn
automatically from your existing TODO state.

* Menu:

* gnosis-journal-todo-files::
* gnosis-journal-todo-keywords::
* Bullet Point Character::
* How TODO Carry-Forward Works::


File: gnosis.info,  Node: gnosis-journal-todo-files,  Next: gnosis-journal-todo-keywords,  Up: ``TODO'' Integration

4.5.1 ‘gnosis-journal-todo-files’
---------------------------------

The list of org files from which TODOs are pulled.  Defaults to
‘org-agenda-files’.

     (setopt gnosis-journal-todo-files org-agenda-files)


File: gnosis.info,  Node: gnosis-journal-todo-keywords,  Next: Bullet Point Character,  Prev: gnosis-journal-todo-files,  Up: ``TODO'' Integration

4.5.2 ‘gnosis-journal-todo-keywords’
------------------------------------

The TODO keywords recognized when scanning files.  Defaults to
‘org-todo-keywords’.  Keywords that appear after the vertical bar ‘|’
(which in standard org convention separates active from done states) are
ignored.

     (setopt gnosis-journal-todo-keywords org-todo-keywords)


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Bullet Point Character,  Next: How TODO Carry-Forward Works,  Prev: gnosis-journal-todo-keywords,  Up: ``TODO'' Integration

4.5.3 Bullet Point Character
----------------------------

The character used to introduce each TODO checkbox in the journal
template output is configured via ‘gnosis-journal-bullet-point-char’.
It defaults to ‘+’, which org-mode renders as a plain-list item.

     (setopt gnosis-journal-bullet-point-char "+")


File: gnosis.info,  Node: How TODO Carry-Forward Works,  Prev: Bullet Point Character,  Up: ``TODO'' Integration

4.5.4 How TODO Carry-Forward Works
----------------------------------

When a journal entry's template is applied, ‘gnosis-journal-todos’ scans
‘gnosis-journal-todo-files’ for headings whose TODO keyword matches an
active keyword from ‘gnosis-journal-todo-keywords’.  It includes items
that either have no scheduled date or are scheduled for today.  Each
included item is rendered as a checkbox line:

     + [ ] Write documentation
     + [ ] Review pull requests


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Checked Item Tracking,  Next: Inserting Journal Links,  Prev: ``TODO'' Integration,  Up: Journal

4.6 Checked Item Tracking
=========================

When you mark a checkbox in a journal entry as done (‘[x]’) and save the
buffer, gnosis identifies all checked items, finds the corresponding
TODO headings in ‘gnosis-journal-todo-files’ by title, and marks them as
‘DONE’.  It also records a ‘LAST_DONE_DATE’ property on the heading so
that the same item is not marked done twice in one day.

   In single-file mode (‘gnosis-journal-file’ non-nil), gnosis restricts
checked-item lookup to the section of the file corresponding to today's
date heading.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Inserting Journal Links,  Next: Full Journal Configuration Example,  Prev: Checked Item Tracking,  Up: Journal

4.7 Inserting Journal Links
===========================

From within any gnosis buffer, you can insert an org-id link to a
journal entry using ‘gnosis-journal-insert’.  It works identically to
‘gnosis-nodes-insert’ but queries journal entries instead of nodes.


File: gnosis.info,  Node: Full Journal Configuration Example,  Prev: Inserting Journal Links,  Up: Journal

4.8 Full Journal Configuration Example
======================================

     (use-package gnosis
       :ensure t
       :custom
       ;; Journal in separate files (default):
       (gnosis-journal-file nil)
       (gnosis-journal-dir "~/Notes/journal/")
       (gnosis-journal-as-gpg nil)
       (gnosis-journal-bullet-point-char "+")
       (gnosis-journal-todo-files org-agenda-files)
       (gnosis-journal-todo-keywords org-todo-keywords)
       (gnosis-journal-templates
        '(("Default" (lambda ()
                       (concat "{*} Daily Notes\n\n"
                               "{*} Goals\n"
                               (gnosis-journal-todos))))
          ("Empty" (lambda () "")))))


